Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Monday! I=E2=80=99m baaaaackkkkk.
I was a little nervous to take a month off, but I=E2=80=99m really happy wi=
th the decision. It was awesome getting to spend a month of family time, an=
d everything they tell you about how wild it is trying to wrangle two kids =
is true. Puja, Dev, and Maya are all happy and healthy, you=E2=80=99re all =
still here, and I couldn=E2=80=99t be more excited to dive back into Not Bo=
ring, recharged if not rested.=C2=A0
To kick things back off, I decided to go where I feel most comfortable: in =
unfamiliar territory. It=E2=80=99s become clear over the past few months th=
at writing about tech, markets, and the future is impossible without some u=
nderstanding of macroeconomics, geopolitics, and energy. =E2=80=9CWe make a=
pps and the world laughs=E2=80=9D is the tech equivalent of =E2=80=9CWe mak=
e plans and God laughs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Since we=E2=80=99ve been away from each other, let me remind you: I=E2=80=
=99m an idiot, and there are people who are a lot smarter on every topic th=
at I write about than I am. I try to read and talk to as many of them as po=
ssible to inform what I write, but especially when we=E2=80=99re talking ab=
out topics as big as we=E2=80=99re talking about today, I=E2=80=99m going t=
o miss a lot of nuance, and probably get some things wrong. We=E2=80=99re l=
earning together. But Not Boring=E2=80=99s mission is to make the world mor=
e optimistic, and I think that to understand what=E2=80=99s coming next and=
 why things might be better than they seem, it=E2=80=99s important to ventu=
re into the great unknown.=C2=A0
Progress in the coming decade and beyond will be dictated by energy, atoms,=
 and bits, and most importantly by how we humans use them. We=E2=80=99ve fo=
cused a lot on bits in Not Boring, and will continue to =E2=80=93 both on t=
heir own and in combination with atoms =E2=80=93 and today=E2=80=99s piece =
is a first attempt of many to understand how they=E2=80=99ll all work toget=
her to kick off the next wave of growth.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Working Harder and Smarter
There=E2=80=99s this incredibly dumb twitter debate that roars out of hiber=
nation every few months about whether or not people have to work a lot to s=
ucceed.=C2=A0
Someone tweets something like, =E2=80=9CYou need to work hard, including ni=
ghts and weekends, to succeed in your career.=E2=80=9D Most recently, this =
very cute (since deleted) tweet set off a firestorm:
Thousands upon thousands of people were seemingly tremendously offended tha=
t a young startup would be evil enough to filter for people who want to wor=
k really hard during the critical first stage of the company=E2=80=99s life=
=2E Oven (Bun) was the focus of the mob=E2=
=80=99s incredulity this time, but =
the response is the same every time:
Productivity =E2=89=A0 Hours Worked
Unless people are getting paid to work more hours, they shouldn=E2=80=99t
Thanks for letting us know where we don=E2=80=99t want to work
Working nights and weekends can lead to burnout=C2=A0
We shouldn=E2=80=99t normalize hustle culture
=E2=80=9CI know a guy who makes $2 million a year and only works 3 hours a =
month.=E2=80=9D
Blah blah blah=C2=A0
People need to work smart, not hard=C2=A0
I actually started writing a post taking a stand on the side of hard work a=
fter reading the reactions to Oven=E2=80=99s tweet right after watching The=
 Bear=E2=80=A6
=E2=80=A6 but there=E2=80=99s no margin in jumping into that argument. Peop=
le have picked their sides. People like getting riled up. This debate is ju=
st a vessel for that.=C2=A0
Plus, it=E2=80=99s a dumb debate because there=E2=80=99s a clear winner: th=
e answer is that to build anything worldchanging, you need to Work both Sma=
rt and Hard.=C2=A0
It is perfectly fine to not want to build something worldchanging, and it=
=E2=80=99s perfectly fine to question which companies even have a shot at m=
aking that kind of impact =E2=80=93 certainly, the worldchanging rhetoric h=
as been co-opted by countless startups that aren=E2=80=99t deserving of it =
=E2=80=93 but in those few cases where the thing you=E2=80=99re building is=
 truly going to Change the World=E2=84=A2=EF=B8=8F, there=E2=80=99s no doub=
t that it will require Hard, Smart Work with a healthy dollop of luck on to=
p.
Anyway, like I said, I don=E2=80=99t want to get into that debate.=C2=A0
The reason I bring it up is that it=E2=80=99s a good framing for a question=
 I=E2=80=99ve been thinking a lot about. In my last essay pre-Maya, Amplifi=
ed Tribalism [ https://substack.com/redirect/732120eb-2dd5-4cce-98c7-0848a7=
293e1e?r=3D9p0gt ], I wrote about another debate taking shape =E2=80=93 phy=
sical versus digital =E2=80=93 and that I wanted to spend time on paternity=
 leave putting my finger on why that dichotomy was also dumb. Instead of ju=
st physical abundance or a purely digital future, I want a combination of b=
oth: an Abundance Renaissance.
As a quick and dirty shorthand, think about the Abundance Renaissance as th=
e lovechild of the Renaissance, the Enlightenment, and the Industrial Revol=
ution, born into the 21st Century.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s lofty, and it=E2=80=99s going to take Hard Work, Smart Work,=
 and luck for it to happen. So let=E2=80=99s use the Hard Work versus Smart=
 Work argument to frame it up. The debate is both symptomatic of today=E2=
=80=99s feeling of stagnation, and metaphorical for the arc of progress.=C2=
=A0
Symptomatic because there=E2=80=99s no progress without hard work, which is=
 well understood by at least rational people. The fact that hard work is co=
ntroversial =E2=80=93 particularly when the hard work involves typing on co=
mputers in air conditioned rooms, often now at home, doing something that y=
ou opted into because it=E2=80=99s either something you love or that you th=
ink will make you the most money or both =E2=80=93 is a sign of the decaden=
ce [ https://substack.com/redirect/f310f2b0-1c43-4009-986c-9401c4e13f3a?r=
=3D9p0gt ] described by Ross Douthat and the lack of seriousness [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/ec3644e2-3d99-49b3-98d7-d2163197e156?r=3D9p0gt ] desc=
ribed by Katherine Boyle. It=E2=80=99s antithetical to progress when the lo=
w-hanging fruit has been picked and the biggest remaining challenges and op=
portunities are really big and really complex. In the coming years, we=E2=
=80=99re going to see the cultural pendulum swing back from Quiet Quitting =
to Hard Work.=C2=A0
But that=E2=80=99s too on the nose. Of course we need to Work Hard to unloc=
k the next level. You think I=E2=80=99ve been cooking in the lab, not writi=
ng the past month, and coming back with a post admonishing you to work hard=
er? C=E2=80=99mon.=C2=A0
What I think is less discussed, and more interesting, is that the Work Hard=
 versus Work Smart debate is a metaphor for the arc of human progress, and =
that an Abundance Renaissance can come about only if we metaphorically Work=
 both Hard and Smart. Luckily, I think we=E2=80=99re on the precipice of th=
e first time in human history during which humanity is able to simultaneous=
ly Work Hard and Smart.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ll start to explain, starting with two charts.=C2=A0
Two Charts
The two charts come from J. Storrs Hall=E2=80=99s Where Is My Flying Car? [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/15554bc3-183a-4a41-9300-2452815a5156?r=3D9p0=
gt ] and, taken together, are among the most striking I=E2=80=99ve come acr=
oss in a long time.=C2=A0
The first shows the Henry Adams Curve. The Henry Adams Curve is the long-te=
rm trend of about 7% annual growth in =E2=80=9Cusable energy available to o=
ur civilization,=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=9Ccan be factored into a 3% populati=
on growth rate, a 2% energy efficiency growth rate, and a 2% growth in actu=
al energy consumed per capita.=E2=80=9D Since the scale in this chart is po=
wer per capita, the Henry Adams Curve, the light blue line in the chart bel=
ow, shows only the 2% annual growth in energy usage per capita component, a=
nd the dark blue line shows actual energy use per capita.=C2=A0
After nearly two centuries of fitting the curve, per capita energy usage fe=
ll off a cliff in the 1970s and then flatlined. If you have your capital-E =
Environmentalist hat on, that might be cause for celebration. If you have y=
our progress hat on, it might be cause for despair.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a question / mystery in the Progress Studies community succ=
inctly summarized by the name of the website WTF Happened In 1971? [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/9c410745-1189-4665-992c-83d8983d2568?r=3D9p0gt ]. A=
 bunch of economic charts that went up and to the right suddenly dropped an=
d/or flatlined in the 1970s. There are a bunch of explanations. Declining p=
er capita energy usage, while it fell off a couple years after 1971 with 19=
73=E2=80=99s Oil Embargo, seems like one of the best.=C2=A0
Obviously, though, there has been some wild progress since the 1970s. Here,=
 it=E2=80=99s useful to look at the second chart. This one shows which pred=
ictions made by scientifically-inclined sci-fi writers in the first half of=
 the 20th Century came true, and which didn=E2=80=99t, based on their energ=
y intensity.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s striking. What it highlights is that sci-fi writers=E2=80=99 p=
redictions about things that require 10 kilowatts (kW) or less of energy ha=
d a good shot of coming true =E2=80=93 with a cluster at 100% prediction fu=
lfillment, and even a couple at 200% prediction fulfillment =E2=80=93 but t=
hat none of their predictions that would have required 100kw or more of ene=
rgy came true.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThat top right half,=E2=80=9D Hall wrote of the quadrant above 10k=
W and 100%, =E2=80=9Crepresents the futures we were promised but were denie=
d. Including flying cars.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
According to Hall, the chart explains that progress continued robustly in o=
ne area =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CMoore=E2=80=99s Law in computing and communicati=
ons=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 in which energy isn=E2=80=99t a major concern, but f=
latlined in the energy-intensive, atoms-based areas that made up so much of=
 the progress up until the 1970=E2=80=99s.
The history of human progress up until the 1970s was largely about enhancin=
g our bodies=E2=80=99 capabilities, using new power sources, methods, and m=
aterials to create more physical things more quickly and cheaply. As Bill G=
ates=E2=80=99 favorite author Vaclav Smil writes in How the World Really Wo=
rks [ https://substack.com/redirect/c34a34d6-96f7-4c8d-b316-a495aac0b4fb?r=
=3D9p0gt ], =E2=80=9CIn two centuries, the human labor to produce a kilogra=
m of American wheat was reduced from ten minutes to less than two seconds.=
=E2=80=9D As a result, the share of the US population working as farmers de=
clined from 83% in 1800 to 1% today. In other words, new energy sources and=
 materials gave humans a way to Work Harder.=C2=A0
The past fifty years=E2=80=99 progress has primarily been about enhancing o=
ur brains=E2=80=99 capabilities, using new computers, algorithms, and modes=
 of communication to create more digital things and connect over 4 billion =
people to the internet. Smil doesn=E2=80=99t provide similar statistics for=
 information, but there=E2=80=99s an equivalent here, something like, =E2=
=80=9CIn 50 years, the brainpower needed to find a piece of information was=
 reduced from an hour (going to the library, finding a book, finding the in=
formation in the book) to less than two seconds (a Google search).=E2=80=9D=
 As Google=E2=80=99s Eric Schmidt said way back in 2010, =E2=80=9CThere wer=
e 5 Exabytes of information created between the dawn of civilization throug=
h 2003, but that much information is now created every 2 days.=E2=80=9D Whi=
le the veracity of the claim is debated, the general point stands. With com=
puters, humans are capable of Working Smarter.
And yet, despite the digital progress, many very smart people agree with Ty=
ler Cowen in his assessment that over the past fifty years, America has bee=
n living through The Great Stagnation [ https://substack.com/redirect/aabb5=
6cc-26ff-4ed6-95aa-312e052b8b11?r=3D9p0gt ]. =C2=A0
Perceived Stagnation
One of the best recent encapsulations of that view comes from Tanner Greer =
of Scholar=E2=80=99s Stage, who asked Has Technological Progress Stalled? [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/fe80910f-fb5e-4fb6-8b08-19d3cc65491e?r=3D9p0=
gt ] in early August. You should read it. Based on an earlier book of Smil=
=E2=80=99s, Energy in Nature and Society [ https://substack.com/redirect/00=
58a1a5-8168-4c09-82fa-cbaf61b1b66b?r=3D9p0gt ], Greer came to believe that:=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CEconomic activity=E2=80=9D is just a fancy way to say =E2=80=9Cene=
rgy put to human use.=E2=80=9D From this perspective fantastical wealth of =
the last two centuries was not caused or enabled by humanity=E2=80=99s expa=
nding energy consumption=E2=80=94wealth is our energy consumption, just pac=
kaged in goods and services.=C2=A0
If we=E2=80=99re simply Working Smarter and not putting more energy to huma=
n use, the logic goes, then we=E2=80=99re not really producing meaningful e=
conomic activity.
Smil=E2=80=99s position, with which Greer agrees, is that we=E2=80=99re sti=
ll coasting off the technical innovations of the period between 1867-1914 =
=E2=80=93 =E2=80=9Cautomobiles, electrification, steel beams, and so forth=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 and that part of what the fuck happened in the 1970s is=
 that we had just run out of gains from that period=E2=80=99s inventions to=
 harvest. =E2=80=9CThe fruits of innovation,=E2=80=9D Greer writes, =E2=80=
=9Cwere not so much ended as expended.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Greer concludes his essay by arguing that:=C2=A0
A future boom will not come from improvements in organization and informati=
on. It will be from inventing new materials to build from, new ways to move=
 what we build, or new sources of energy to power our building.=C2=A0
For this reason I am bearish on the long run economic impact of supercomput=
ers. Like other information age technologies, all they do is coordinate, or=
ganize, and calibrate existing modes of production. Something like nanotech=
nology or bioengineered materials are more promising, for they promise to r=
eshape the physical basis of our built environments.
I agree with the idea that we need more energy, materials, and modes of tra=
nsportation =E2=80=93 something that Hall espouses in his book, too =E2=80=
=93 but vehemently disagree on information age technologies=E2=80=99 role i=
n making those things come to life.=C2=A0
The perception of a Great Stagnation over the past 50 years could be descri=
bed as a shift from Working Harder (more energy usage, more atoms innovatio=
n) to Working Smarter (better computing, more bits innovation).=C2=A0
My hunch is that there=E2=80=99s been a feeling of Stagnation because the b=
enefits of atoms-based innovations are the kind that make more people feel =
richer and happier than bits-based innovation alone. Getting a refrigerator=
, car, color TV, or airline ticket for the first time is persistently life-=
changing in a way that=E2=80=99s hard for an app to be. We need to build mo=
re physical things =E2=80=93 houses, flying cars, faster planes, affordable=
 cures for diseases, spaceships, and much, much more.=C2=A0
But neither Hard Work nor Smart Work can meet the challenge alone. If the l=
ow-hanging fruits from the last boom have been picked, we need to create a =
new boom.=C2=A0
How are we expected to invent new materials, modes of transport, and source=
s of energy without tapping into the improvements in organization and infor=
mation we=E2=80=99ve harnessed over the past 50 years? The next stage of at=
oms-based innovation will be harder and more complex to unlock than the las=
t.=C2=A0
The sweet spot, as ever, is working both Harder and Smarter.=C2=A0
We need to create and consume more energy, not less. And we need to combine=
 atoms-based innovation with the five decades worth of progress we=E2=80=99=
ve made in the world of bits.=C2=A0
So how to reverse the trend? While countless factors played a role in mater=
ial stagnation =E2=80=93 from bureaucracy and regulation to specialization =
and increasing complexity =E2=80=93 I like Hall=E2=80=99s Henry Adams Curve=
 and Sci-Fi Predictions Chart=E2=80=99s focus on energy. It=E2=80=99s simpl=
e to pick and optimize for one variable, and energy usage is relatively eas=
y to measure.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s focus on energy. For our purposes, more cheap, clean energy c=
onsumption is good, less cheap, clean energy consumption is bad.=C2=A0
(Of course, if we just try to maximize this variable by any means necessary=
, we=E2=80=99re no better than the paperclip-producing AI. This post [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/c20bac96-2194-4aa0-91b5-b6a89ad0729a?r=3D9p0gt ],=
 for example, argues that Bitcoin mining will get us back on the Henry Adam=
s Curve, and if we consume that much more energy just to mine Bitcoin, I uh=
hh don=E2=80=99t think it will have been a success.)=C2=A0
Luckily, we=E2=80=99re on the cusp of an energy transition. New energy para=
digms create entirely new ecosystems around them. Steam engines enabled ste=
el, railroads, skyscrapers, and even corporations. Fossil fuels powered car=
s, planes, polymers, plastics, and booming globalization. Abundant clean en=
ergy, too, will reshape cities, transportation, and even the global balance=
 of power, but it will require the best of our bits innovation to maximize =
its potential and coordinate the potentially more distributed systems it ma=
kes possible.=C2=A0
I think that if we don=E2=80=99t fuck it up (which, we=E2=80=99re human, so=
 we might), we have a shot at an Abundance Renaissance that combines Workin=
g Harder (more energy usage) with Working Smarter (better computing technol=
ogy) at a scale we=E2=80=99ve never been able to reach in human history to =
date.=C2=A0
If The Great Stagnation isn=E2=80=99t over yet, it=E2=80=99s about to be.=
=C2=A0
So let=E2=80=99s dig into that energy transition.=C2=A0
Energy and Atoms=C2=A0
Whoever was responsible for clean energy=E2=80=99s branding over the past c=
ouple decades needs to be fired and potentially tried for crimes against hu=
manity.=C2=A0
Clean energy isn=E2=80=99t about efficiency and replacing dirty fuels with =
clean ones. It=E2=80=99s about being able to do more and better, creating m=
aterial abundance and distributing it more evenly across the world, and mov=
ing past the long stage of human history in which we fight each other for s=
carce resources and squabble over petty things out of a sense of scarcity-i=
nduced frustration. It=E2=80=99s about getting back on, and even ahead of, =
the Henry Adams Curve without fucking the planet.=C2=A0
Fortunately, despite the awful branding, the Clean Energy Transition seems =
to be happening right under our noses, and is picking up steam thanks in pa=
rt to the impacts of the War in Ukraine. In this section, we=E2=80=99ll cov=
er:=C2=A0
Energy is wealth
The shifting energy narrative
The Clean Energy Transition
The benefits of Energy Superabundance
Energy is Wealth
Let=E2=80=99s start with something that should be apparent, but has been do=
wnplayed in the push for efficiency: energy is really important.=C2=A0
Energy lets humans =E2=80=9CWork Harder=E2=80=9D while actually doing less =
manual labor ourselves. This 2016 post [ https://substack.com/redirect/adb2=
fbde-4600-40bd-865f-d517da92d8d8?r=3D9p0gt ] calculated that each American =
has the equivalent of =E2=80=9Cnearly 600 full-time =E2=80=98human energy s=
ervants=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D thanks to energy consumption. Even the most arden=
t Hard Work supporters would never argue that people should work 14,400 hou=
rs per day, but that=E2=80=99s the leverage that energy gives us. And that =
=E2=80=9CHard Work=E2=80=9D can work wonders for an economy.=C2=A0
An overly simple way to think about a country=E2=80=99s wealth is the amoun=
t of energy each of its citizens is able to consume. As a quick sanity chec=
k on that claim, here=E2=80=99s a chart of the countries in the world ranke=
d by per capita kilowatt hours (kWh) consumed per year.
There=E2=80=99s nuance here. Iceland=E2=80=99s electricity consumption, for=
 example, looks so much higher than everyone else=E2=80=99s because, thanks=
 to its cheap and abundant geothermal energy, it=E2=80=99s become the de fa=
cto aluminum smelting capital of the world, which drives up its energy cons=
umption (while keeping its CO2 emissions per capita much lower than the Uni=
ted States or China). But that in and of itself is an argument for abundant=
 clean energy as a strategic priority; Iceland has been able to attract lar=
ge multinational companies, with their money and jobs, because of it.=C2=A0
As a piece of personal anecdata, I got the chance to catch up with my old A=
u Pair, Gry, a few years ago because of the effects of this chart. Gry is f=
rom the #2 country on this chart, Norway, and she and her husband came to v=
isit New York City because it was cheaper for them to fly to the US and buy=
 their Christmas presents in our most expensive city than it was to buy the=
m in Norway. That blew my mind. They were essentially trading their country=
=E2=80=99s energy riches for our country=E2=80=99s goods.=C2=A0
Overall, that chart looks like a good proxy for wealth. The countries with =
the most energy consumption per capita are countries you=E2=80=99d expect t=
o see at the top of a wealth list =E2=80=93 Iceland, Norway, Bahrain, Qatar=
, Finland, Canada, Kuwait, Sweden, United Arab Emirates, and United States =
=E2=80=93 and the countries with the least are the ones you=E2=80=99d expec=
t to see at the bottom =E2=80=93 Chad, Guinea-Bissau, Somalia, Burundi, Cen=
tral African Republic, Sierra Leone, Haiti, South Sudan, Rwanda.=C2=A0
Any big diffs between the per capita energy consumption list and the per ca=
pita GDP list seem to largely be accounted for by small populations and bus=
iness-friendly regulations: Lichtenstein, Monaco, Luxembourg, Bermuda, Irel=
and, Switzerland, Cayman Islands, and Singapore are all countries with high=
er GDPs per capita than the US without natural energy advantages. They=E2=
=80=99re also all tax havens [ https://substack.com/redirect/f66b2ce9-1ba7-=
496a-b1f1-deea7548c609?r=3D9p0gt ].
With the enormous caveat that I=E2=80=99m not an energy or macroeconomics e=
xpert, and that I=E2=80=99m sure I=E2=80=99m dramatically oversimplifying i=
n a way that would make real experts throw up, energy abundance seems to be=
 a pretty clean way to think about economic abundance.
That point, and the paragraphs supporting it above, are so obvious-sounding=
 when you write them out that it seems almost silly to waste the ink (and y=
our time) on them, but personally, even though my first real job was on an =
energy trading desk, it=E2=80=99s one that I hadn=E2=80=99t really given mu=
ch thought to recently. The defining narrative of the past decade when it c=
omes to energy is that we need to use less of it, not more.=C2=A0
That narrative is shifting.=C2=A0=C2=A0
To read about the Energy Narrative Shift, the Clean Energy Transition, and =
what it might look like to Work Harder and Smarter=E2=80=A6
Thanks to Dan for editing, and to our friends at Secureframe [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/ca79e22c-2e0f-4c5f-b021-fa5a307d8401?r=3D9p0gt ] for spon=
soring!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. Catch you on Thursday for a special Founder=
=E2=80=99s Letter.
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

