a Leone, Haiti, South Sudan, Rwanda.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Any big diffs =
between the per capita energy consumption list and the per capita GDP list =
seem to largely be accounted for by small populations and business-friendly=
 regulations: Lichtenstein, Monaco, Luxembourg, Bermuda, Ireland, Switzerla=
nd, Cayman Islands, and Singapore are all countries with higher GDPs per ca=
pita than the US without natural energy advantages. They&#8217;re also all =
</span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/f66b2ce9-1ba7-496a-b1f1-dee=
a7548c609?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: und=
erline;">tax havens</a><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>With the enormous c=
aveat that I&#8217;m not an energy or macroeconomics expert, and that I&#82=
17;m sure I&#8217;m dramatically oversimplifying in a way that would make r=
eal experts throw up, </span><strong>energy abundance seems to be a pretty =
clean way to think about economic abundance</strong><span>.</span></p><p st=
yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
0;"><span>That point, and the paragraphs supporting it above, are so obviou=
s-sounding when you write them out that it seems almost silly to waste the =
ink (and your time) on them, but personally, even though my first real job =
was on an energy trading desk, it&#8217;s one that I hadn&#8217;t really gi=
ven much thought to recently. The defining narrative of the past decade whe=
n it comes to energy is that we need to use </span><em>less</em><span> of i=
t, not more.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">That narrative is shifting.&#160;&#16=
